STEP 3–>
STEP 4 - Use a permutation approach - Inference to generate a null distribution of F statistic values for the model of log(Mass) in relation to Trophic.Level and calculate a p value for your original F statistic.
Do this either by: 1. programming your own permutation test (e.g., by shuffling values for the predictor or response variable among observations and calculating an F statistic for each replicate)
or
2. by using the {infer} workflow and setting calculate(stat=“F”).

before I can compute permuted F-statistic values, I must compute the ACTUAL/original F-stat for log_Mass and Tropic.Level

r documentation shows that the calculate() function from {infer} workflow can compute the F-stat easily- https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/infer/versions/1.0.5/topics/calculate

(similar use of the functions I will be using for permuted f stats)

library(infer)

(original.F <- d_filtered %>%
  specify(log_Mass ~ Trophic.Level) %>%
  calculate(stat = "F"))
## Response: log_Mass (numeric)
## Explanatory: Trophic.Level (factor)
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##    stat
##   <dbl>
## 1  78.2

now I can follow our methology from Module 16 (or more specific to this, Module 20.5) and generate a permutation test

permuted.F <- d_filtered %>%
  specify(log_Mass ~ Trophic.Level) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>%
  calculate(stat = "F")


# plot
visualize(permuted.F) +
  shade_p_value(obs_stat=original.F, direction="greater")
## Warning in min(diff(unique_loc)): no non-missing arguments to min; returning
## Inf

get p-value

(p.value <- permuted.F %>%
  get_p_value(obs_stat = original.F, direction="greater"))
## Warning: Please be cautious in reporting a p-value of 0. This result is an approximation
## based on the number of `reps` chosen in the `generate()` step.
## ℹ See `get_p_value()` (`?infer::get_p_value()`) for more information.
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##   p_value
##     <dbl>
## 1       0

STEP 3 –>
Run ANOVA analyses to look at the association between geographic range size and the variable Migration.
- drop those observations for which Migration is not scored - look at the distribution of the variable Range.Size - decide whether and how it might need to be transformed.
QUESTIONS: - Based on the global model, is range size associated with form of migration? - How much of the variance in your measure of range size is associated with Migration behavior style? - Given the regression coefficients returned in the output of the model, which Migration categor(ies) are different than the reference level? - What level is the reference level? Relevel and assess differences among the remaining pair of Migration categories.
Also conduct a post-hoc Tukey Honest Significant Differences test to also evaluate which Migration categories differ “significantly” from one another (see Module 20).
ANSWERS: - the ANOVA results show a very high F-statistic value (above the critical value) with a very low p-value, suggesting a significant association between range size and migration - the R-squared value from the linear model summary tells us what percentage of the variance in Range.Size is associated with Migration behavior; from my linear model I got 0.08681 or around 8.7% (which honestly surprised me a little, I thought it would be higher?) - The reference level is Migration type 2, and both types 1 and 3 seem to be different from it - AFTER RELEVELING: 1 and 3 also seem to be more different from one another - none of the CI’s from the Tukey test cross over zero, meaning that all three types of migration differ significantly from one another

STEP 6–>
Finally, run an additional two-way model with the same dataset and predictors, but adding the possibility of an interaction term.
To do this, you should modify your model formula using the colon operator (:) to specify the interaction, e.g., relative beak length ~ Primary.Lifestyle + Trophic.Level + Primary.Lifestyle:Trophic.Level.
QUESTION: - Based on the model output, what would you now conclude about how relative beak length is related to these two variables?
ANSWER: - looking at the p-value for the F-stat in “Primary.lifestyle:Trophic.Level” interactions row, the interaction between these two variables IS SIGNIFICANT. this suggests that primary lifestyle and trophic level are somewhat codepedent upon one another, in addition to influencing beak length.
once again I’m referencing to Module 20.8 to use the colon operator
r m <- aov(data = passeriformes, rel_Beak ~ Primary.Lifestyle + Trophic.Level + Primary.Lifestyle:Trophic.Level) # the colon (:) operator includes specific interaction terms summary(m)

  trace.factor = passeriformes$Primary.Lifestyle,
  trace.label = "primary lifestyle",
  x.factor = passeriformes$Trophic.Level,
  xlab = "trophic level",
  response = passeriformes$rel_Beak,
  fun = base::mean, # make sure we use {base} version
  ylab = "relative beak length"
)
